{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"931"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/931"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.05,0.13,0.1,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43478"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/931"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"931"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28471"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"576"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"58"},{"type":"contributions","id":"59"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10961"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43478"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents after an episode of visual disturbance. He describes the visual changes as having difficulty seeing things to his left, like he was \u2018blind, but only to one side in both eyes\u2019. During the episode, he noted being dizzy, as if the room was spinning. He had no headache, pain with eye movements or prodromal symptoms, and the symptoms resolved after about ten minutes. He has never had a similar episode before. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension. His medications include gliclazide and diltiazem. His blood pressure is 140/85mmHg and pulse 80/min and regular. His left fundus is shown in the photograph. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior circulation ischaemia","Ocular Migraine","Retinal artery emboli","Central retinal vein occlusion","Optic neuritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are no retinal abnormalities shown on the pictured fundus. This question focuses on identifying the location of a lesion along the visual pathway. The description of a homonymous hemianopia, rather than a monocular field defect, is suspicious of a pathology posterior to the optic chiasm rather than of the optic nerve or retinal artery. A homonymous hemianopia can  be secondary to pathology affecting the optic tract or occipital cortex (macula-sparing homonymous hemianopia). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the options given, transient \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemia in the right posterior circulation\u003C/strong\u003E (thus affecting the visual cortex) is most likely to explain the contralateral visual disturbance. Additionally, the patient\u2019s vertigo symptoms can occur in the setting of posterior cerebral artery ischaemia. Notably, the patient\u2019s medical history predisposes him to cerebrovascular events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E: This option is less likely due to the described visual symptoms being bilateral, transient and having associated vertigo; which are not typical features of retinal artery occlusion. Additionally, retinal artery occlusion tends to cause sudden and painless unilateral  loss of vision, which is permanent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcular migraines\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with visual disturbances(an aura), such as zigzag lines, scintillating scotomas or shimmering lights, followed by a headache. The duration of the aura is variable but is often longer than ten minutes, and there is usually a history of migraine headaches. Given the patient\u0027s vascular risk factors this is not the most likely diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects young females presenting with unilateral visual loss, often accompanied by pain with eye movements, especially upon gaze to the affected side. The described symptoms affecting both eyes simultaneously and the absence of pain with eye movements make optic neuritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painless, sudden-onset visual loss, often described as a curtain coming down over the vision. It does not typically cause difficulty recognizing objects/people or affect both eyes simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A transient ischaemic attack is an important diagnosis to consider and exclude in older patients presenting with sudden visual loss."],"references":["Nouh A, Remke J, Ruland S. Ischemic posterior circulation stroke: a review of anatomy, clinical presentations, diagnosis, and current management. Front Neurol. 2014;5:30. Published 2014 Apr 7. doi:10.3389/fneur.2014.00030","Ehlers JP, Shah CP. The Wills eye manual: Office and emergency room diagnosis and treatment of eye disease. Philadelphia: Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2016"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28471"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"931"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"802"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/802"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg"